article.headline: Lewis, Christon, Vaden put away Stephen F. Austin
article.linkText: Powerful trio leads No. 16 Arkansas to easy victory
article.story:
FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- India Lewis scored 19 points and
Shameka Christon added 18 Saturday night as Arkansas (No. 16 ESPN/USA Today; No. 17 Associated Press) beat
Stephen F. Austin 78-54 in the season opener for both teams.

	   Ruby Vaden, a 6-foot-3 point guard from Osceola, Ark., almost had a
double-double game with nine rebounds and 15 points.

	   ''I would have done even better if I hadn't missed so many
shots,'' said Vaden, who finished 5-for-13.

	   Arkansas shot 38.5 percent to 35.6 percent for Stephen F.
Austin. But Arkansas forced 28 turnovers and held a
53-41 rebounding edge. Arkansas scored 25 points off turnovers, to
15 for Stephen F. Austin.

	   Christon was 8-for-15 from the field, and she and Vaden each
pulled down nine rebounds. Christon blocked four shots.

	   LaToya Mills led Stephen F. Austin with 15 points, Nathesia
Wright added 13. Amy Collins scored 11.

	   Arkansas worked on its outside game, attempting 18 3-pointers;
Lewis was 3-for-12 from beyond the line.

	   ''I didn't shoot as well as I hoped,'' Lewis said, ''but in zone
defense, that's my role is to take the outside shot.''

	   Stephen F. Austin shot only five 3s, making three. Neither team
distinguished itself from the foul line. Arkansas made 13 of 24,
while Stephen F. Austin made nine of 17.

	   Mills made seven of 11 field goal attempts, and grabbed nine
rebounds, seven of them on defense. Stephen F. Austin had 14
second-chance points, to 22 for Arkansas.

	   Arkansas coach Gary Blair said he borrowed stealing rebounding
plays used by the men's team, and the move paid off as the
Arizona amassed 53 rebounds, breaking the women's previous
record of 49 against Kentucky last year.

	   ''That's good because it means we're picking up our misses and
finishing our shots,'' Blair said.

	   ''We took off like we were at the Kentucky Derby,'' Blair said.
''They had to play us zone, because if we faced man we would have
scored a whole lot more than we did.''

	   Stephen F. Austin coach Lee Ann Riley said she enjoyed coaching
against her former boss Blair, who gave her defensive pointers in
the media workroom after the game.

	   ''Personally, it was a fun game for me ... but I'm not grateful
we got beat,'' Riley said, who had a 24-6 record in her first
season as head coach. ''I didn't come up here to lose.''
